//CSFLE

At a high level, we add the KMS driver dependency and the rule.executors._default_.param.* properties, everything else is done under the hood with the java client.

//Serializer looks up the schema + ruleSet (where your ENCRYPT rule is defined) for each subject.
//Serializer calls EncryptionExecutor (generic field encryption engine)
//EncryptionExecutor looks at encrypt.kms.type and calls the appropriate driver
//KmsDriver is user to build an KMS client 
//For first time EncryptionExecutor Generates a random data encryption key (DEK) in memory.
//Calls KmsDriver → KmsClient → KMS Encrypt methid with your credentials to wrap that DEK under your KEK 
//Sends the wrapped DEK and metadata to the DEK registry REST API, which stores it 
//On the Producer Side the Serializer Uses the plaintext DEK (obtained by decrypting the stored DEK via KMS). Uses AEAD to encrypt those bytes. 
//On the Consumer side we fetch the DEK from the DEK registry; use KMS Decrypt (through AwsKmsDriver) to unwrap it.


